---
/** Lifestyle: eldercare cost projection. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import EldercareCostCalculator from '../../components/calculators/EldercareCostCalculator.tsx';
import { eldercareCost } from '../../lib/lifestyle';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = eldercareCost('assisted', 'med', 4, 0.04);
const nursing = eldercareCost('nursing', 'vhigh', 4, 0.04);
---

<Base
  title="Eldercare cost calculator 2026"
  description="What long-term care really costs: assisted living, memory care and nursing homes by state cost tier, projected over the years of care with inflation."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Lifestyle</p>
    <h1>The cost of eldercare</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Long-term care is the expense most retirement plans underestimate — and Medicare doesn't cover it. Here's what it runs, by type and state.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Long-term care is the biggest gap in most retirement plans, because people assume Medicare covers it. It doesn't
    cover custodial care — help with daily living, which is what most eldercare is. This projects the cost by care
    type and state cost tier over the years it's needed, so the number is concrete rather than a vague worry.
  </p>

  <EldercareCostCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>Four years of assisted living in a medium-cost state, versus a nursing home in a very-high-cost state:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Total (4 years)</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Assisted living, medium-cost state</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.monthlyCost)}</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.totalCost)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nursing home, very-high-cost state</td><td>{formatMoney(nursing.monthlyCost)}</td><td>{formatMoney(nursing.totalCost)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Four years of assisted living runs about {formatMoney(ex.totalCost)}; a nursing home in an expensive state can be
    {' '}{formatMoney(nursing.totalCost)}. These are the numbers that drain a lifetime of savings in a few years —
    and why long-term-care insurance and Medicaid planning exist.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Doesn't Medicare pay for this?</h3>
    <p>No. Medicare covers short rehab stays after a hospitalization, not ongoing custodial care — the help with
      bathing, dressing and meals that makes up most long-term care. That cost falls on savings, insurance, or
      Medicaid.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>When does Medicaid step in?</h3>
    <p>Medicaid covers long-term care, but only after you've spent down assets to a low threshold. That's why families
      plan years ahead — asset transfers have a five-year look-back, so last-minute moves don't work.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How accurate are these figures?</h3>
    <p>They're reference US averages by care type, scaled to a broad state cost tier and inflated 4%/year. Real quotes
      vary widely by facility and city — treat this as a planning range, then get local quotes.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/when-can-i-retire-calculator/">When can I retire?</a> — build the care cost into the plan</li>
    <li><a href="/net-worth-calculator/">Net worth</a> — what's available to fund it</li>
    <li><a href="/death-and-money-calculator/">Death &amp; money</a> — what's left afterward</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">Care costs are approximate reference averages by state tier, not local quotes. Not financial advice.</p>
</Base>
